ate." The speech continues to loom large in Germany's struggle to acknowledge responsibility for Nazi crimes yet escape a suffocating burden of remembrance. But in spiteof its notoriety, little attention has been paid to what the speech actually says, as opposed to the public outcry and debate that followed it. This book presents the text of the speech, along with several of Walser's other essays and speeches about the Holocaust and its impact on German identity, in English translation. It examines them as texts, a process that involves a discussion of literary complexities and an attempt to distinguish valid criticism of German intellectual life from what is justifiably problematic. And it places this textual examination in the context of Walser's and other postwar German intellectuals' attempts to deal with the Nazi past, of German-Jewish relations in the postwar era, and of the once hidden and now -- due in part to Walser's speech -- increasingly open discourse about Germans as victims during and immediately after the Nazi era. Thomas A. Kovach is Professorof German Studies at the University of Arizona.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic books. -- local. 0aGermany -- History -- 1933-1945. 0aGermany -- History. 0aWalser, Martin, -- 1927- -- Political and social views. 0aWalser, Martin,x1927-xPolitical and social views. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aGerman-Jewish Relations.  aGermans as Victims.  aMartin Walser.  aNazi Past.  aPeace Prize Speech.1 aWalser, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113789040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isb